WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.040
You know, usually when we talk about a medical diagnosis, there's this expectation of like extreme precision.

00:08.300 --> 00:10.140
Right. Yeah. Feels like engineering.

00:10.580 --> 00:15.540
You break your arm. The x-ray shows that jagged white line right there on the screen.

00:15.680 --> 00:19.120
And the doctor just points it and says, ah, there it is.

00:19.500 --> 00:23.740
Exactly. It's entirely binary. It's broken or it's not broken.

00:24.020 --> 00:27.580
It's a very clean, observable reality.

00:27.580 --> 00:31.760
And it's a comforting. Like we desperately like things to be visible.

00:31.960 --> 00:34.260
We want to categorize them neatly in a box.

00:34.500 --> 00:38.460
But then you step into the world of modern media consumption.

00:38.580 --> 00:39.900
Oh, boy. Right.

00:40.040 --> 00:44.120
You step into this digital ecosystem we all live in every single day.

00:44.220 --> 00:48.180
And suddenly that x-ray machine is just completely useless.

00:49.080 --> 00:55.940
We're looking at a diagnostic landscape of our own attention spans that is honestly incredibly murky.

00:55.940 --> 00:59.760
It is the absolute definition of diagnostic muddy waters.

01:00.040 --> 01:01.620
The symptoms are everywhere, obviously.

01:01.820 --> 01:07.200
But the underlying disease process is, well, it's largely invisible to the naked eye.

01:07.560 --> 01:12.320
I want you, the listener, to think about your own scrolling habits for a second.

01:12.440 --> 01:13.620
Maybe it was late last night.

01:14.680 --> 01:22.720
Have you ever spent an hour or maybe even longer just swiping through brilliant bite-sized cliffs?

01:23.040 --> 01:24.840
Just completely lost in the feed?

01:24.840 --> 01:25.740
Yeah, exactly.

01:26.040 --> 01:26.240
Yeah.

01:26.340 --> 01:28.940
Someone is explaining macroeconomics in 40 seconds.

01:29.140 --> 01:34.000
And the next swipe is a fascinating historical fact about the Roman Empire.

01:34.260 --> 01:39.920
And then a life-changing psychological framing about how to, you know, talk to your kids.

01:40.020 --> 01:40.820
High-quality.

01:41.240 --> 01:43.920
Really dense, high-quality information.

01:43.920 --> 01:48.700
And then you finally lock your phone, you log off, and you feel completely empty.

01:49.380 --> 01:55.340
Like, you cannot remember a single, cohesive argument from the last 60 minutes of your life.

01:55.400 --> 01:59.060
It's a very specific, deeply hollow feeling.

01:59.220 --> 02:06.720
I mean, you have just consumed a thousand distinct puzzle pieces, yet you possess absolutely no picture at all.

02:06.720 --> 02:11.920
And the mission of this Deep Talk today is to explore exactly why that happens.

02:12.040 --> 02:17.300
Because, spoiler alert, it is not because your attention span is fundamentally broken.

02:17.480 --> 02:18.540
No, not at all.

02:18.580 --> 02:20.200
Your brain is not failing you.

02:20.620 --> 02:27.080
The system you are participating in is functioning exactly mathematically as it was designed to function.

02:27.080 --> 02:30.560
That is the core revelation we are exploring today.

02:31.040 --> 02:39.400
We are diving into a singular, incredibly dense, and, frankly, absolutely fascinating theoretical paper.

02:39.620 --> 02:40.440
It really is.

02:40.500 --> 02:40.720
Yeah.

02:40.960 --> 02:46.960
It was published in April 2026 by an independent researcher who goes by the name Fliction.

02:47.480 --> 02:55.260
The paper is titled Recomposable Fragmentation, a Field Theoretic Critique of the Clip Economy.

02:55.260 --> 02:57.340
I love that title so much.

02:57.420 --> 03:03.720
It sounds like something I would read in a theoretical physics journal, not, you know, a media studies class.

03:03.960 --> 03:08.120
Well, what's so fascinating about this work is that it basically is a physics paper.

03:08.660 --> 03:11.420
Fliction doesn't do the usual cultural hand-wringing.

03:11.440 --> 03:11.680
Right.

03:11.820 --> 03:13.900
None of the kids these days on their phones stuff.

03:13.920 --> 03:14.400
Exactly.

03:14.980 --> 03:22.700
This paper doesn't spend 20 pages complaining about screen time or relying on vague, unquantifiable critiques about societal isolation.

03:22.700 --> 03:38.560
Instead, Fliction applies actual physics and advanced mathematics, specifically something called the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum, or RSVP Field Theory, to diagnose the underlying architecture of modern media.

03:38.980 --> 03:40.060
Okay, I have to be honest.

03:40.160 --> 03:47.320
When I first saw the phrase RSVP Field Theory in our notes, I genuinely panicked a little bit.

03:47.540 --> 03:51.080
I thought we were going to need a whiteboard.

03:51.080 --> 03:52.700
A lot of people feel that way.

03:53.060 --> 03:58.380
But the goal today isn't to get bogged down in the differential equations, right?

03:58.500 --> 03:58.700
Right.

03:59.060 --> 04:07.440
We are going to translate those profound structural models to completely change how you view your media diet.

04:07.920 --> 04:08.480
Precisely.

04:08.480 --> 04:18.200
And if you make things, whether that's podcasts, essays, or even just internal memos at work, this might change how you create information, too.

04:18.200 --> 04:23.680
We are essentially mapping out the thermodynamic physics of the social media feed.

04:24.120 --> 04:31.980
And to even begin that process, Fliction argues we have to understand what they term an ontological inversion in human communication.

04:32.260 --> 04:33.340
Ontological inversion.

04:33.460 --> 04:33.660
Okay.

04:34.600 --> 04:36.720
That sounds incredibly dramatic.

04:36.880 --> 04:38.880
Break down what that actually looks like in practice.

04:38.880 --> 04:44.580
It is dramatic, but it's also this quiet revolution that happened right under our noses.

04:44.840 --> 04:48.220
Look, historically, short-form media is not a new invention.

04:48.460 --> 04:48.560
Right.

04:48.620 --> 04:49.740
We've had commercials forever.

04:50.160 --> 04:50.680
Exactly.

04:51.200 --> 04:55.500
Movie trailers, newspaper headlines, 30-second radio spots.

04:56.000 --> 05:06.700
But historically, the fundamental nature, the ontology, right, of the clip, was that it served as a promotional teaser for a longer, cohesive work.

05:06.700 --> 05:12.980
So you watched the two-minute trailer so that you would eventually go sit in a theater for two hours.

05:13.140 --> 05:13.420
Yes.

05:13.640 --> 05:13.880
Yeah.

05:14.640 --> 05:17.900
The clip was a signpost pointing to a destination.

05:18.440 --> 05:22.960
The ontological inversion means the clip has ceased to be a signpost.

05:23.080 --> 05:24.760
It's not pointing anywhere anymore.

05:24.800 --> 05:26.020
It's no longer a teaser.

05:26.260 --> 05:30.560
It has become the primary terminal unit of consumption.

05:31.120 --> 05:32.600
It is the main event.

05:32.740 --> 05:33.960
It's not the appetizer.

05:34.220 --> 05:35.520
It's the entire meal.

05:35.520 --> 05:42.960
Content is now engineered from the ground up so that any 30-second window is entirely locally self-sufficient.

05:44.000 --> 05:55.320
I was really struck by the paper's concept of the clipping army because, you know, it used to be that you'd make a two-hour documentary and maybe someone in the marketing department would cut a 30-second promo to run on TV.

05:56.160 --> 05:58.680
Now, the clipping army isn't an afterthought.

05:58.940 --> 06:00.980
It is the core content architecture.

06:00.980 --> 06:02.800
That is a crucial distinction.

06:03.600 --> 06:06.900
And we see this acutely in the streaming world, for instance.

06:07.540 --> 06:13.980
A live streamer might have 10,000 concurrent viewers watching them play a game or give an interview live.

06:14.220 --> 06:15.660
That's a solid audience.

06:15.820 --> 06:16.100
Sure.

06:16.100 --> 06:21.100
But that same streamer will generate billions of views over the next two weeks.

06:21.700 --> 06:21.980
How?

06:22.880 --> 06:38.360
Because there are coordinated armies, some human, some fully automated bots that are doing nothing but clipping and distributing tiny fragments of that stream across every short-form platform simultaneously.

06:38.360 --> 06:41.120
So the live broadcast isn't even the product.

06:41.380 --> 06:43.660
The live broadcast is just a quarry.

06:43.920 --> 06:44.420
A quarry.

06:44.520 --> 06:45.660
That's a great way to put it.

06:45.800 --> 06:49.180
It's raw material to be mined by the clipping army.

06:49.540 --> 06:53.360
The digital archive isn't a library of finished works anymore.

06:53.700 --> 06:56.860
It's just a reservoir of extractable mullets.

06:56.860 --> 07:06.340
And this is exactly where Fliction brings in the RSVP field theory to explain the mechanics of why this mining operation is so devastatingly effective.

07:06.940 --> 07:12.220
They model the entire clip economy as a driven, dissipative field system.

07:12.380 --> 07:13.600
Okay, let's pause right there.

07:13.840 --> 07:15.920
A driven, dissipative field system.

07:16.060 --> 07:17.720
Give me a tangible way to picture that.

07:18.140 --> 07:20.080
Think of it as a thermodynamic engine.

07:20.440 --> 07:21.240
Like a hurricane.

07:21.900 --> 07:22.700
Okay, a hurricane.

07:23.020 --> 07:26.020
A hurricane is a driven, dissipative system.

07:26.020 --> 07:29.000
It is driven by the heat of the ocean.

07:29.520 --> 07:33.080
And it dissipates that energy through wind and rain.

07:33.440 --> 07:38.040
It is a structure that only exists because of a massive flow of energy.

07:38.440 --> 07:38.560
Right.

07:38.760 --> 07:40.620
Without the warm water, it just falls apart.

07:40.780 --> 07:41.280
Exactly.

07:41.760 --> 07:44.160
The clip economy is the exact same thing.

07:44.900 --> 07:50.700
It requires a massive, constant flow of human attention to sustain its structure.

07:50.700 --> 07:58.480
And to understand how it directs that attention, RSVP field theory gives us three key variables.

07:58.720 --> 07:59.700
Let's take them one by one.

07:59.760 --> 08:00.960
I want to be sure I'm following this.

08:01.320 --> 08:01.660
Perfect.

08:02.200 --> 08:07.000
The first variable is the scalar field, represented by the Greek letter phi.

08:07.000 --> 08:11.940
In this mathematical model, phi represents engagement potential.

08:12.460 --> 08:19.020
So phi is just the pure, raw probability that someone will stop swiping and actually watch the video.

08:19.080 --> 08:19.340
Yes.

08:19.820 --> 08:21.680
The likelihood of momentary capture.

08:22.300 --> 08:27.300
If a clip has high phi, it means it possesses qualities that arrest the thumb.

08:27.440 --> 08:29.640
Like bright colors or a sunny movement.

08:29.640 --> 08:34.160
Right, or an inflammatory statement, or a recognizable celebrity face.

08:34.720 --> 08:41.540
And critically, Fiction points out that phi is maximized when the clip requires absolute zero prior context.

08:41.900 --> 08:50.300
Because if I need to know what happened in part one, or if I need to know the historical background of the person speaking, my brain has to do work.

08:50.400 --> 08:50.840
Exactly.

08:51.280 --> 08:56.760
And if your brain has to do work, the likelihood of your thumb stopping drops drastically.

08:56.760 --> 09:01.020
So high context requirements act as friction, lowering phi.

09:01.180 --> 09:02.080
Okay, I get that.

09:02.260 --> 09:03.300
What's the second variable?

09:03.780 --> 09:07.860
The second variable is the vector field, denoted by a lowercase v.

09:08.400 --> 09:14.580
If phi is the inherent stickiness of the clip, the vector field is the distributional flux.

09:15.100 --> 09:19.500
It is the literal movement of the content through the network.

09:19.500 --> 09:29.400
So this would be the recommendation algorithm itself, plus human amplification-like people, sharing it to group chats, retweeting it, that sort of thing.

09:29.560 --> 09:29.940
Correct.

09:30.220 --> 09:34.620
The vector field is the current carrying the object down the stream.

09:34.960 --> 09:37.260
The algorithm is constantly measuring phi.

09:37.640 --> 09:44.820
And when it detects a spike, it massively increases the vector field, pushing that clip onto millions of screens.

09:45.000 --> 09:47.680
Okay, so phi is the bait, the inherent hook.

09:47.680 --> 09:50.760
The vector field is the current carrying the bait to the fish.

09:51.080 --> 09:52.420
That leaves the third variable.

09:52.760 --> 09:53.180
What is that?

09:53.720 --> 09:57.260
The third is entropy, represented by the letter S.

09:57.660 --> 10:03.680
And in the context of information theory, entropy is quite literally context loss.

10:04.580 --> 10:06.560
Entropy as context loss.

10:07.240 --> 10:09.220
That feels profound.

10:09.840 --> 10:14.860
Because normally in our day-to-day lives, losing context is seen as a mistake.

10:15.000 --> 10:15.700
Oh, absolutely.

10:15.700 --> 10:18.940
If I jump into a conversation halfway through, I'm confused.

10:19.080 --> 10:19.660
It's an error.

10:20.040 --> 10:20.280
Right.

10:20.440 --> 10:31.380
But if we connect this to the broader laws of thermodynamics, specifically Landauer's principle, we uncover a really dark truth about the feed.

10:31.640 --> 10:33.280
Walk me through Landauer's principle.

10:33.280 --> 10:39.160
So Landauer's principle states that erasing information is thermodynamically irreversible.

10:39.560 --> 10:42.040
It actually costs energy to erase data.

10:42.840 --> 10:50.920
But in the specific environment of the clip economy, high entropy, meaning high context loss, is an immense evolutionary advantage.

10:51.020 --> 10:52.700
I really need you to unpack that for me.

10:52.960 --> 10:57.240
How does stripping context from a piece of information actually help it survive?

10:57.240 --> 11:02.460
Because high context loss directly correlates to a lower cognitive load for the viewer.

11:02.700 --> 11:06.320
Think about a nuanced two-hour debate on economic policy.

11:06.800 --> 11:08.480
It has incredibly low entropy.

11:09.120 --> 11:11.720
All the context is deeply woven together.

11:12.560 --> 11:18.200
To understand point D, you must have already internalized points A, B, and C.

11:18.720 --> 11:21.340
That requires sustained cognitive effort.

11:21.460 --> 11:22.820
You really have to pay attention.

11:22.820 --> 11:23.420
Exactly.

11:24.220 --> 11:33.640
But if a clipping bot extracts a five-second moment where one debater just rolls their eyes in size and then puts a funny sound effect over it.

11:33.660 --> 11:39.080
They've stripped away all the economic policy, all the history, all of the dependencies are just gone.

11:39.280 --> 11:40.980
They've radically increased the entropy.

11:41.300 --> 11:41.600
Yes.

11:42.040 --> 11:49.560
And by removing all those complex dependencies, that five-second clip becomes incredibly easy to consume.

11:49.560 --> 11:52.300
It requires zero background knowledge.

11:52.820 --> 11:57.740
The lower the cognitive load, the wider the population of viable receivers becomes.

11:57.940 --> 11:59.460
Because anyone can understand it.

11:59.540 --> 11:59.760
Right.

12:00.260 --> 12:02.220
My grandmother can understand an eye roll.

12:02.560 --> 12:05.460
A teenager halfway across the world can understand an eye roll.

12:05.660 --> 12:10.120
By increasing entropy, you directly increase the engagement potential.

12:10.620 --> 12:11.240
The phi.

12:11.720 --> 12:15.520
The system actively mathematically selects against coherence.

12:15.520 --> 12:23.360
So stripping context is like, imagine you were trying to transport a beautiful, historic brick house across the country.

12:23.440 --> 12:24.280
Oh, I like this.

12:24.340 --> 12:24.620
Okay.

12:25.060 --> 12:30.580
If you try to move it whole, you need wide load permits, a massive truck.

12:31.000 --> 12:32.240
It takes weeks.

12:32.360 --> 12:33.800
You have to worry about low bridges.

12:34.160 --> 12:35.700
It's incredibly slow.

12:35.840 --> 12:36.720
Lots of friction.

12:36.720 --> 12:37.280
Right.

12:37.280 --> 12:49.120
But if you take a sledgehammer, smash the house into individual bricks, throw them in a dump truck, and hit the gas, you can move those bricks at 80 miles an hour.

12:49.360 --> 12:54.360
You get a massive amount of material moving at incredible speeds.

12:54.920 --> 12:58.900
The only problem is when you get to the destination, you don't have a house anymore.

12:59.140 --> 13:00.740
You just have a pile of bricks.

13:00.740 --> 13:04.960
That is a stunningly accurate visualization of the vector field.

13:05.600 --> 13:12.340
The system rewards speed and volume, and the structural integrity of the house is an active impediment to both.

13:12.680 --> 13:14.920
But let me play devil's advocate here for a second.

13:15.060 --> 13:16.680
Let me push back on Fliction's premise.

13:16.940 --> 13:25.640
Because the standard defense from Silicon Valley, from the people building these platforms, is that this is just a pure, democratic, free market of attention.

13:25.900 --> 13:27.720
The old free market defense, yes.

13:27.720 --> 13:30.720
They argue they aren't forcing anything on anyone, right?

13:31.580 --> 13:37.720
They are just neutrally giving the people the easy, frictionless content they naturally crave.

13:38.300 --> 13:44.460
If people truly wanted to our economic debates, the algorithm would supposedly serve them.

13:44.460 --> 13:46.700
That is indeed the standard defense.

13:47.080 --> 13:54.480
But Fliction rigorously refutes the neutral free market argument using a concept they call the occupation tensor.

13:55.080 --> 13:56.140
The occupation tensor.

13:56.140 --> 13:58.140
Again, with heavy physics jargon.

13:58.580 --> 14:01.100
What does that actually mean in terms of my feed?

14:01.300 --> 14:10.040
To understand the occupation tensor, we have to look at how the vector field, the distribution network, actually operates at a massive scale.

14:10.040 --> 14:15.460
The algorithm does not just passively transport a clip from creator to viewer.

14:16.020 --> 14:18.260
It is strategically overdriven.

14:18.960 --> 14:22.880
The vector field splits into two distinct mathematical components.

14:22.880 --> 14:27.660
A transport component and an occupation component.

14:27.720 --> 14:28.840
Okay, transport makes sense.

14:28.920 --> 14:31.020
That's just moving data from the server to my phone.

14:31.460 --> 14:33.000
What is the occupation component?

14:33.000 --> 14:39.180
The occupation component performs what the paper terms, a territorial saturation of the attentional manifold.

14:39.580 --> 14:40.680
Territorial saturation.

14:41.320 --> 14:41.840
Wow.

14:41.840 --> 14:44.120
So we were talking about actual warfare now.

14:44.120 --> 14:47.560
In the informational space, it absolutely is warfare.

14:48.080 --> 14:51.320
Think about how coordinated clipping operations work.

14:52.200 --> 14:59.420
When a major cultural event happens, the clipping armies don't just produce one definitive summary video.

14:59.460 --> 15:00.840
No, you see thousands of them.

15:00.840 --> 15:01.420
Exactly.

15:01.540 --> 15:10.320
They seed thousands upon thousands of slightly altered variants of the exact same moment across the algorithm simultaneously.

15:10.720 --> 15:19.200
They change the crop, alter the captions slightly, maybe pitch shift the audio a fraction of a percent to evade duplicate filters.

15:19.460 --> 15:20.620
Why do they do that, though?

15:20.920 --> 15:24.780
Why not just push one really good, high-quality clip?

15:25.100 --> 15:27.180
Because the goal is not just to be seen.

15:27.180 --> 15:35.400
The goal is to occupy every single available coordinate in the attention space so that literally nothing else can exist there.

15:35.900 --> 15:36.740
It is territorial.

15:37.300 --> 15:44.540
The operating logic of the system is if we do not occupy this specific slot in a user's feed, a competitor will.

15:45.000 --> 15:52.000
So they pump an unimaginable volume of low-context, high-engagement content into the system just to take up space.

15:52.340 --> 15:52.600
Exactly.

15:52.600 --> 15:54.080
Oh, I see.

15:54.080 --> 16:03.620
So if I open my app, and the first 30 videos I swipe through are just variations of the same meaningless celebrity gossip or the same viral prank,

16:03.860 --> 16:09.200
it's not necessarily because my deep, true desire is to watch 30 prank videos.

16:09.400 --> 16:13.560
It's because the occupation tensor has completely saturated the space.

16:14.020 --> 16:14.460
Right.

16:14.460 --> 16:24.300
The background radiation of this high-entropy content is so intense that anything requiring even a second of thought is literally squeezed out.

16:25.140 --> 16:30.220
Flexition notes that the system treats compositional structure as impedance drag.

16:30.460 --> 16:38.900
Impedance drag, meaning any requirement to slow down and think, is treated by the network as a malfunction to be routed around.

16:38.900 --> 16:44.320
Yes. If a video requires you to know what happened a minute ago, it slows down the transport layer.

16:44.680 --> 16:49.720
So coherence is not lost by accident, and it's not lost merely because of human laziness.

16:50.180 --> 16:57.560
Coherence is actively, algorithmically designed out of the production process to maximize flow and territorial occupation.

16:57.560 --> 17:06.320
So if the feed is this thermodynamic engine actively destroying context to maximize flow, how do we even begin to measure success?

17:06.500 --> 17:12.840
Because all the metrics we use, views, likes, shares, they all assume we are measuring something whole.

17:13.160 --> 17:15.360
Right. They assume a coherent object.

17:15.660 --> 17:22.540
We have to look at what happens when a clip is stripped down to its absolute irreducible minimum.

17:22.540 --> 17:30.420
Which brings us to the second major concept in this paper, the atomic limit.

17:31.040 --> 17:33.260
The atomic limit is a brilliant concept.

17:33.780 --> 17:46.920
Flexition defines it as the point where a fragment of media shrinks so much, both in its physical duration and in its contextual footprint, that reconstruction is literally mathematically impossible.

17:46.920 --> 18:01.460
So it's not just that the brick is separated from the house, it's that the brick has been pulverized into dust, and there is no possible way to reverse engineer the architectural blueprints of the house from a handful of dust.

18:01.800 --> 18:03.580
Exactly. You've hit the nail on the head.

18:04.000 --> 18:08.500
In information theory, this is described as reaching a pure Shannon signal.

18:08.700 --> 18:12.800
Let's define that for the listener, because Claude Shannon is a huge figure in this space.

18:12.860 --> 18:13.500
Real massive.

18:13.500 --> 18:16.760
Claude Shannon is essentially the father of information theory.

18:17.480 --> 18:21.160
Back in the 1940s, he figured out how to measure digital information.

18:21.920 --> 18:28.020
But a crucial part of Shannon's genius was separating the transmission of a signal from its actual meaning.

18:28.160 --> 18:28.980
Okay, how so?

18:28.980 --> 18:40.500
Well, for a telecom engineer, a string of random garbage data is the exact same amount of information as a beautiful Shakespeare sonnet, as long as they take up the same bandwidth.

18:40.500 --> 18:48.060
A pure Shannon signal is data transmission completely divorced from human meaning.

18:48.060 --> 18:52.460
So an atomic clip has zero pragmatic redundancy.

18:53.000 --> 18:56.300
There is no breadcrumb trail back to the original thought.

18:56.680 --> 18:59.200
It is just an isolated flash of light on a screen.

18:59.200 --> 18:59.640
Yes.

19:00.280 --> 19:08.640
And fliction proves mathematically that when a media ecosystem reaches this atomic limit, popularity becomes non-integrable.

19:08.860 --> 19:09.680
Non-integrable.

19:09.800 --> 19:11.080
Let's unpack that term.

19:11.600 --> 19:15.160
In calculus, integrating is about finding the hole, right?

19:15.260 --> 19:16.560
The area under the curve.

19:16.660 --> 19:16.900
Yeah.

19:16.980 --> 19:19.900
Adding up all the tiny slices to see the big picture.

19:19.900 --> 19:20.540
Exactly.

19:21.060 --> 19:24.100
In a healthy mathematical system, you can integrate the parts.

19:24.560 --> 19:24.720
Yeah.

19:24.800 --> 19:32.600
But in the clip economy, a million views on a million isolated atomic fragments do not add up to a coherent whole.

19:33.160 --> 19:36.520
The platforms measure success by counting additive views.

19:37.020 --> 19:41.820
100,000 likes on this 10-second clip, a million views on that reaction, Jif.

19:42.060 --> 19:45.280
The algorithm treats engagement as a flat multi-set.

19:45.500 --> 19:47.400
It is just a pile of numbers.

19:47.500 --> 19:48.760
But it's structurally blind.

19:48.760 --> 19:49.980
Completely blind.

19:50.380 --> 20:01.720
It has no mechanism to determine whether those millions of views are actually building into what the paper calls a curved manifold of actual understanding in the mind of the viewer.

20:01.880 --> 20:03.240
A curved manifold.

20:03.460 --> 20:03.700
Yeah.

20:03.840 --> 20:13.200
A manifold is simply a topological space that locally resembles flat space, but globally can have complex structure like the surface of the Earth.

20:13.300 --> 20:16.560
The algorithm only sees the flat local space.

20:16.560 --> 20:25.600
It's like, imagine trying to judge the quality and depth of a massive Russian novel, like say, War and Peace.

20:25.700 --> 20:25.960
Okay.

20:26.260 --> 20:26.940
War and Peace.

20:27.040 --> 20:33.800
And you judge it by writing a computer script that just counts how many times the letter E appears in the text.

20:33.940 --> 20:35.480
That is a phenomenal analogy.

20:35.640 --> 20:36.320
I love that.

20:36.320 --> 20:40.040
The script runs and it comes back and says, incredible success.

20:40.240 --> 20:42.720
We have registered 50,000 letter E's.

20:42.780 --> 20:44.640
This is a highly engaging book.

20:45.360 --> 20:52.440
You have a massive, mathematically verifiable number at the end, but you possess zero story.

20:52.440 --> 20:57.540
You have no characters, no plot, no themes, just a massive pile of E's.

20:57.760 --> 21:01.700
The algorithm looks at the feed and says, look at this incredible engagement.

21:02.040 --> 21:02.960
Look at the E count.

21:03.360 --> 21:06.420
But the integral diverges structurally.

21:06.780 --> 21:12.360
You cannot stitch those pieces back into the original geometry of the source material.

21:12.700 --> 21:16.580
This actually sheds a completely new light on the idea of the filter bubble.

21:16.580 --> 21:19.900
We've been talking about the filter bubble for a decade, right?

21:20.920 --> 21:29.860
Eli Perzer coined the term to describe how algorithms only show us political opinions we already agree with, trapping us in an echo chamber.

21:30.240 --> 21:30.620
Right.

21:30.620 --> 21:41.380
But Flixian argues the political filter bubble is actually a downstream symptom of this deeper architectural flaw, this atomic limit.

21:41.700 --> 21:42.100
Wait, really?

21:42.220 --> 21:46.520
So it's not a deliberate political conspiracy by the platforms to divide us?

21:46.660 --> 21:48.000
Not necessarily, no.

21:48.180 --> 21:48.980
Think about it.

21:49.380 --> 22:01.040
A system optimized solely for purely additive, context-free engagement necessarily fails to track whether the accumulated engagements build into anything coherent.

22:01.040 --> 22:04.160
It doesn't know what it's feeding you, only that you keep swiping.

22:04.480 --> 22:04.920
Exactly.

22:05.200 --> 22:11.240
It just keeps handing you more of the same letter E because it noticed you lingered on an E for 1.4 seconds.

22:11.900 --> 22:15.540
The ideological isolation is almost an accident of the thermodynamics.

22:16.080 --> 22:16.360
Wow.

22:16.580 --> 22:30.200
So if the system is pumping out billions of these atomic fragments and measuring its own success by these completely meaningless additive metrics, what happens to the human being on the receiving end?

22:30.200 --> 22:32.200
That is the critical question.

22:32.200 --> 22:36.920
Because human brains did not evolve to process isolated Shannon signals.

22:37.480 --> 22:39.040
We evolved to build narratives.

22:39.220 --> 22:43.020
We evolved to find the structural walls to map our environment.

22:43.360 --> 22:50.960
If we are forced to consume 10,000 context-free fragments a day, our brains have to be buckling under the strain.

22:50.960 --> 22:52.740
And they absolutely are.

22:52.740 --> 22:57.540
Which takes us to one of the most profound and unsettling sections of the paper.

22:58.320 --> 23:03.080
Phase 3, exploring semantic torsion and the Burnout Society.

23:03.520 --> 23:04.560
Semantic torsion.

23:04.660 --> 23:04.840
Okay.

23:04.940 --> 23:06.840
Torsion usually means twisting or tearing.

23:07.040 --> 23:07.240
Right.

23:07.340 --> 23:09.020
Like a torsion spring in mechanics.

23:09.240 --> 23:09.580
Yes.

23:10.140 --> 23:18.480
Flickshahn borrows the term torsion specifically from differential geometry, where it is used to measure the failure of something called parallel transport.

23:18.480 --> 23:24.400
Okay, we are definitely going to need an ELI-5 explain, like I'm 5 for parallel transport.

23:25.100 --> 23:26.080
Because you've lost me.

23:26.140 --> 23:27.560
Okay, let's visualize a globe.

23:27.820 --> 23:28.240
Got it.

23:28.500 --> 23:28.920
A globe.

23:29.060 --> 23:33.040
Imagine you are standing on the equator, facing directly north.

23:33.500 --> 23:33.860
Okay.

23:34.080 --> 23:38.460
You hold a stick straight out in front of you, pointing directly at the north pole.

23:39.180 --> 23:46.600
Now, you start walking north all the way to the pole, keeping that stick pointing exactly the way you are walking.

23:46.600 --> 23:49.660
Okay, I'm at the north pole, stick pointing forward.

23:50.000 --> 23:53.260
Now, without turning your body, you sidestep.

23:53.540 --> 23:57.020
You slide sideways down the globe until you hit the equator again.

23:57.460 --> 23:59.640
The stick is still pointing north.

23:59.900 --> 24:01.320
Still pointing north, check.

24:01.680 --> 24:06.760
Finally, you sidestep along the equator back to your exact starting position.

24:06.760 --> 24:13.200
You have moved the stick while keeping it strictly parallel to its own path the entire time.

24:13.700 --> 24:22.260
But when you return to your exact starting point, you will find that the stick is pointing in a completely different direction than when you started.

24:22.500 --> 24:24.480
Wait, really? Just from sidestepping?

24:24.700 --> 24:25.100
Yes.

24:25.620 --> 24:28.180
Because the surface of the globe is curved.

24:28.580 --> 24:29.620
That is wild.

24:29.620 --> 24:38.520
That orientation shift, the fact that forward changes depending on the path you take across a curved surface, is a result of the curvature of the space.

24:39.020 --> 24:43.960
That failure of the stick to match its original orientation is torsion.

24:44.380 --> 24:47.740
Okay, that is a fantastic geometrical concept.

24:48.100 --> 24:48.300
Yeah.

24:48.480 --> 24:56.860
But how does parallel transport on a globe apply to me watching a podcast clip on my phone while I'm, like, waiting in line for coffee?

24:56.860 --> 25:14.060
In the media field, semantic torsion is the cognitive experience of encountering the exact same argument or the exact same public figure across different clips, but finding that the local interpretations are entirely mathematically incompatible.

25:14.360 --> 25:16.780
Give me a tangible example of how that plays out.

25:17.040 --> 25:23.660
Let's say there is a prominent tech CEO giving a two-hour interview about artificial intelligence.

25:24.440 --> 25:26.200
That interview is the globe.

25:26.200 --> 25:32.520
Now, you see a 15-second clip on Monday where they discuss the medical breakthroughs AI will bring.

25:33.280 --> 25:36.540
Locally, in that one clip, they sound like a utopian visionary.

25:36.740 --> 25:37.880
It makes total sense.

25:38.200 --> 25:38.600
Okay, yeah.

25:38.900 --> 25:43.020
Then on Wednesday, you encounter another 15-second clip from the same interview.

25:43.300 --> 25:51.680
But this one is heavily edited by a different clipping bot, overlaid with ominous music, highlighting a warning about job losses.

25:52.740 --> 25:55.280
Locally, they sound like a doomsday prepper.

25:55.280 --> 25:59.160
So both clips make sense in their tiny 15-second bubbles.

25:59.660 --> 26:00.000
Right.

26:00.300 --> 26:09.540
But because the global frame, the larger curved context of the two-hour nuance discussion, has been destroyed by the entropy of the feed,

26:10.040 --> 26:16.820
you cannot embed these fragments into a single consistent understanding of that CEO's philosophy.

26:16.820 --> 26:19.680
Because the stick is pointing in two different directions.

26:19.880 --> 26:20.480
Exactly.

26:21.200 --> 26:28.540
You are trying to parallel transport their ideas across your feed, and the stick keeps pointing in contradictory directions.

26:28.600 --> 26:29.000
Oh, man.

26:29.660 --> 26:36.060
My brain literally cannot make the pieces fit together without introducing massive contradictions.

26:36.060 --> 26:38.160
And your brain hates contradictions.

26:38.360 --> 26:39.100
So what happens?

26:39.720 --> 26:41.900
You experience cognitive amnesia.

26:42.400 --> 26:45.460
You just forget the first clip to make room for the second.

26:45.940 --> 26:52.260
You are constantly tearing down and rebuilding tiny, fragile models of reality that collapse seconds later.

26:52.800 --> 26:56.000
That constant tearing is semantic torsion.

26:56.000 --> 27:03.420
I want you to think about the last time you felt totally profoundly burnt out by the news, or by a social media argument.

27:03.940 --> 27:05.780
You usually blame it on screen time, right?

27:06.080 --> 27:07.140
Or blue light.

27:07.420 --> 27:10.340
Or just the overall negativity of the world.

27:10.460 --> 27:11.720
It's the easy scapegoat.

27:11.720 --> 27:16.320
But this paper is arguing that your brain wasn't just physically tired.

27:17.220 --> 27:21.180
Your trajectory-based cognition was structurally collapsing.

27:21.920 --> 27:28.180
You were being handed puzzle pieces from a thousand different boxes, pieces that were cut to incompatible shapes,

27:28.180 --> 27:33.180
and the system was implicitly demanding that you build one cohesive picture.

27:34.040 --> 27:34.400
Exactly.

27:34.660 --> 27:35.960
Of course you're burnt out.

27:36.140 --> 27:38.180
It is literally an impossible task.

27:38.180 --> 27:43.760
Affliction connects this phenomenon directly to the work of philosopher Bing Chulhan,

27:44.180 --> 27:46.660
specifically his book The Burnout Society,

27:47.120 --> 27:53.540
and even draws a line to Viktor Frankl's psychological observations on the human need for meaning.

27:54.460 --> 27:59.700
In the context of the clip economy, burnout is not a failure of personal effort.

28:00.400 --> 28:02.640
It's not a lack of willpower or discipline.

28:03.020 --> 28:04.860
No, it's an environmental hazard.

28:04.860 --> 28:12.360
It is the literal neurological accumulation of semantic torsion beyond your brain's recovery threshold.

28:13.320 --> 28:17.440
The system demands that you integrate information to make sense of your world,

28:17.760 --> 28:23.140
while simultaneously actively starving you of the structural context required to do so.

28:23.380 --> 28:25.520
It is a psychological double bind.

28:25.700 --> 28:29.360
And there's a really strong connection here to behavioral economics, right?

28:29.500 --> 28:30.560
Daniel Kahneman's work.

28:30.860 --> 28:31.720
Very much so.

28:31.720 --> 28:37.180
Kahneman's famous framework divides our thought processes into System 1 and System 2.

28:37.960 --> 28:42.800
System 1 is our fast, automatic, intuitive, closure-seeking processing.

28:43.080 --> 28:48.480
It reacts to a loud noise, it reads a facial expression, it jumps to a quick conclusion.

28:48.740 --> 28:49.060
Right.

28:49.220 --> 28:54.780
And System 2 is the slow, deliberate, analytical, structure-building processing.

28:55.180 --> 29:00.640
It does math, it follows complex logic, it holds conflicting ideas in tension.

29:00.640 --> 29:03.980
So how does the feed interact with those two systems?

29:04.460 --> 29:10.060
The clip economy continuously, relentlessly rewards and stimulates System 1.

29:10.300 --> 29:15.160
Every 15 seconds, a new microtension is introduced and immediately resolved.

29:15.800 --> 29:21.220
A joke is told, a punchline hits, a problem is stated, a life hack is provided.

29:21.700 --> 29:25.220
It provides a constant drip of dopamine and fast closure.

29:25.500 --> 29:29.200
But it completely systematically starves System 2.

29:29.200 --> 29:35.260
Because System 2 needs time to build the house, and the feed is just throwing bricks at your head at 80 miles an hour.

29:35.340 --> 29:36.300
Man, that's brutal.

29:36.740 --> 29:37.240
It is.

29:37.240 --> 29:50.400
If you inhabit a field where literally all informational inputs are optimized for immediate, context-free resolution, the cognitive skill of maintaining open structure begins to atrophy.

29:51.040 --> 29:59.620
The ability to hold tension over time, to defer closure in order to synthesize a deeper truth, becomes physically uncomfortable.

29:59.620 --> 30:03.320
So the pathology of the digital age is incredibly clear here.

30:03.620 --> 30:08.960
The problem isn't that a TikTok video or a YouTube short is too short in its duration.

30:09.320 --> 30:11.360
10 seconds isn't inherently evil.

30:11.760 --> 30:15.700
The problem is that the media fundamentally cannot be put back together.

30:16.100 --> 30:17.820
The pieces are broken by design.

30:17.880 --> 30:19.240
Broken by design, yes.

30:19.240 --> 30:29.300
So if we accept this reality, the burning question becomes, how do we define the difference between a shattered, useless piece of media and a healthy, useful building block?

30:29.780 --> 30:34.760
This is where Flickshian pivots from diagnosing the disease to prescribing the cure.

30:34.920 --> 30:35.240
Yes.

30:35.500 --> 30:39.720
This brings us to phase four of the paper, diagnosing the fragments.

30:39.720 --> 30:46.700
Flickshian introduces a rigorous framework to define what they call recomposable fragmentation, because let's be realistic.

30:47.280 --> 30:49.220
We cannot put the genie back in the bottle.

30:49.360 --> 30:51.760
We are going to live in a fragmented media landscape.

30:52.340 --> 30:52.500
Right.

30:52.820 --> 30:57.640
The economic and energetic flows are far too massive to reverse entirely.

30:58.340 --> 31:03.480
We can't all go back to solely reading hardcover encyclopedias by candlelight.

31:03.720 --> 31:05.280
The river's flowing too fast.

31:05.760 --> 31:06.240
Exactly.

31:06.240 --> 31:11.080
So if we must have fragments, we need fragments that can actually be recombined.

31:11.260 --> 31:11.380
Right.

31:11.660 --> 31:18.840
And a recomposable fragment system must satisfy three specific mathematical and logical conditions.

31:19.080 --> 31:19.920
Let's walk through them.

31:20.020 --> 31:20.260
Okay.

31:20.620 --> 31:21.780
What is the first condition?

31:22.140 --> 31:24.860
The first is R1, extraction validity.

31:25.500 --> 31:31.160
This simply means that the fragment makes coherent sense when viewed entirely on its own.

31:31.560 --> 31:34.380
Well, the clip economy already does this brilliantly.

31:34.380 --> 31:36.340
The 30-second hook works.

31:36.800 --> 31:37.580
The joke lands.

31:37.860 --> 31:37.980
Right.

31:38.680 --> 31:39.620
R1 is easy.

31:40.180 --> 31:42.240
The failure happens at the next two steps.

31:42.700 --> 31:45.960
The second condition is R2, compositional gain.

31:46.500 --> 31:52.940
This means that if I take fragment A and I consume it alongside fragment B from the same source,

31:53.300 --> 31:54.740
they must gain meaning.

31:55.280 --> 31:57.280
The sum must be greater than the parts.

31:57.660 --> 32:00.800
They must lock together to build a larger conceptual structure.

32:00.800 --> 32:07.500
And as we just discussed with the atomic limit, the modern clip economy violently violates R2.

32:07.720 --> 32:10.640
A thousand clips of that tech CEO just give you a headache.

32:11.100 --> 32:15.820
They give you juxtaposition and torsion, not deeper philosophical meaning.

32:16.400 --> 32:19.140
It's just noise piled on top of noise.

32:19.280 --> 32:19.720
Precisely.

32:19.820 --> 32:20.920
So what's the third condition?

32:21.220 --> 32:25.180
The third condition is R3, order sensitivity.

32:25.180 --> 32:31.280
This means that the chronological order in which you consume the fragments matters to the nuance

32:31.280 --> 32:32.040
of the argument.

32:32.860 --> 32:36.040
But altering the order doesn't completely break the system.

32:36.740 --> 32:42.760
Consuming fragment A then B might yield a slightly different insight than consuming B then A.

32:42.980 --> 32:47.840
But both pathways maintain a fundamental structural coherence.

32:47.840 --> 32:50.460
So it's flexible, but not chaotic.

32:51.340 --> 32:58.580
And the paper gives a truly brilliant historical example of a medium that solved this recomposable

32:58.580 --> 33:02.860
fragmentation perfectly decades before the algorithm ever existed.

33:03.020 --> 33:04.740
Yes, the art of stand-up comedy.

33:04.920 --> 33:06.600
I loved this section so much.

33:06.760 --> 33:09.880
Think about a masterful, hour-long stand-up comedy special.

33:10.420 --> 33:15.680
The comedian has built the show out of modular units, bits, jokes, crowd work segments.

33:15.680 --> 33:16.620
These are fragments.

33:17.320 --> 33:21.620
A comedian can take a single three-minute bit and perform it on a late-night talk show.

33:21.940 --> 33:23.600
And it makes perfect sense alone.

33:23.800 --> 33:26.320
It satisfies R1, extraction validity.

33:26.560 --> 33:27.620
And it doesn't stop there.

33:27.980 --> 33:28.340
Right.

33:28.840 --> 33:32.740
If you go to the comedy club and hear three or four of those bits performed in a row,

33:33.100 --> 33:36.340
you start to understand the comedian's overarching worldview.

33:36.800 --> 33:38.340
Their persona comes into focus.

33:38.660 --> 33:41.340
The jokes gain meaning by being together.

33:41.720 --> 33:44.820
That satisfies R2, compositional gain.

33:45.100 --> 33:45.620
Exactly.

33:46.360 --> 33:51.780
And a great comedian can completely shift the order of the jokes on the fly based on the

33:51.780 --> 33:52.940
energy of the crowd.

33:53.460 --> 33:58.160
The order matters to the flow of the evening, but the set still structurally works.

33:58.640 --> 34:01.700
That satisfies R3, order sensitivity.

34:02.680 --> 34:05.660
Stand-up comedy evolved to be perfectly recomposable.

34:05.660 --> 34:14.140
But the modern clip economy, governed by the RSVP vector field, aggressively destroys R2 and R3.

34:14.140 --> 34:18.900
It creates what fliction terms degenerate fragment systems.

34:19.400 --> 34:24.240
And the paper identifies three specific failure modes for these broken fragments.

34:24.480 --> 34:27.560
It basically categorizes the junk in our feeds.

34:27.700 --> 34:27.840
Right.

34:27.840 --> 34:29.160
Let's categorize the junk.

34:29.220 --> 34:30.600
What is the first failure mode?

34:30.600 --> 34:32.500
The first is the terminal fragment.

34:32.840 --> 34:34.500
This is an absolute dead end.

34:34.720 --> 34:40.140
It resolves tension locally, gives you a quick system one dopamine hit, and admits absolutely

34:40.140 --> 34:41.840
no path for reconstruction.

34:41.840 --> 34:44.060
Give me an example of a terminal fragment.

34:44.440 --> 34:47.540
Think of a video of someone simply falling over.

34:48.020 --> 34:52.280
Or a deeply satisfying video of power washing a driveway.

34:52.580 --> 34:53.640
Oh, I love those.

34:53.640 --> 34:54.560
We all do.

34:54.940 --> 34:56.760
But it is pure sensation.

34:57.200 --> 34:59.540
It begins, it peaks, it ends.

35:00.140 --> 35:05.980
It is designed to terminate your traversal of ideas, not trigger a deeper one.

35:06.040 --> 35:06.900
It's a cul-de-sac.

35:07.120 --> 35:11.060
You drive into the neighborhood, you look at the nice house, but the road just loops back

35:11.060 --> 35:11.580
on itself.

35:11.700 --> 35:14.800
You have to turn around and leave exactly the way you came in.

35:15.180 --> 35:16.840
You can't get anywhere else from there.

35:16.920 --> 35:17.480
Exactly.

35:17.480 --> 35:21.000
The second failure mode is the drift fragment.

35:21.620 --> 35:23.640
This is a much more insidious fragment.

35:24.480 --> 35:31.960
Its meaning actively degrades over time through repeated transportation and recontextualization, much

35:31.960 --> 35:35.900
like accumulating measurement errors in a scientific experiment.

35:36.180 --> 35:36.880
How does that happen?

35:37.140 --> 35:43.380
Every time it gets clipped, duetted, reacted to, or parodied, the implicit context shifts

35:43.380 --> 35:43.880
slightly.

35:43.880 --> 35:50.160
Eventually, it points to a reality completely unmoored from its original source.

35:50.360 --> 35:52.080
That's the playground game of telephone.

35:52.580 --> 35:55.940
The teacher whispers, the purple monkey washed the dishes.

35:56.420 --> 36:01.920
By the time it reaches the 20th kid in the circle, it has drifted so far that the kid

36:01.920 --> 36:05.780
shouts out, global thermonuclear war is imminent.

36:06.260 --> 36:07.600
That is exactly it.

36:07.860 --> 36:13.500
A nuanced scientific study about the correlation between coffee and heart rates drifts until

36:13.500 --> 36:17.320
headline screams, scientists prove coffee cures cancer.

36:17.940 --> 36:23.220
The drift fragment survives by mutating until it maximizes phi regardless of truth.

36:23.620 --> 36:23.840
Wow.

36:24.180 --> 36:24.420
Okay.

36:24.520 --> 36:25.960
What is the third failure mode?

36:26.320 --> 36:31.280
The third and frankly most dangerous failure mode is the adversarial fragment.

36:31.780 --> 36:38.560
This is a fragment that has been intentionally hijacked to point to a fake source or a fabricated

36:38.560 --> 36:39.200
context.

36:39.520 --> 36:40.400
Hijacked how?

36:40.760 --> 36:41.500
Like maliciously?

36:41.500 --> 36:42.220
Maliciously.

36:42.220 --> 36:42.620
Yes.

36:43.060 --> 36:45.720
It exploits the fact that it makes sense locally.

36:46.520 --> 36:53.360
It has R1 extraction validity, but it deliberately routes the receiver toward an entirely different,

36:53.760 --> 36:58.100
structurally incompatible conclusion than the original work intended.

36:58.780 --> 37:03.700
Imagine a clip of a politician saying, I will raise your taxes, but stripping the first half

37:03.700 --> 37:06.640
of the sentence where they said, my opponent's plan guarantees that.

37:06.640 --> 37:07.200
Okay.

37:07.300 --> 37:12.920
This is where the theory gets terrifyingly real because an adversarial fragment isn't

37:12.920 --> 37:16.740
just a cul-de-sac and it isn't just a harmless game of telephone.

37:17.160 --> 37:21.380
An adversarial fragment is someone sneaking out in the middle of the night and physically

37:21.380 --> 37:23.480
switching the road signs on the highway.

37:23.700 --> 37:24.840
That's a perfect analogy.

37:25.120 --> 37:30.160
You think you're driving safely to the city center, but they've explicitly routed you off

37:30.160 --> 37:30.620
a cliff.

37:30.620 --> 37:35.560
And here is the critical vulnerability of the entire internet.

37:36.420 --> 37:42.880
The algorithm, the vector field, treats a high engagement adversarial fragment exactly

37:42.880 --> 37:45.680
the same as it treats a truthful one.

37:45.960 --> 37:47.600
Because it only sees phi.

37:48.020 --> 37:50.180
It only measures engagement potential.

37:50.400 --> 37:51.160
Precisely.

37:51.720 --> 37:54.920
The thermodynamic system only selects for phi.

37:54.920 --> 38:01.660
It is completely mathematically blind to what Fliction calls recovery map integrity.

38:02.160 --> 38:04.900
It cannot verify if the road sign is real.

38:05.300 --> 38:10.580
If the fake road sign gets a lot of people to stop and look at it, the system prints 10

38:10.580 --> 38:14.340
million more fake road signs and plasters them everywhere.

38:14.780 --> 38:18.180
Okay, so we know exactly what the broken fragments look like.

38:18.660 --> 38:23.960
We have the terminal dead ends, the drifting game of telephone, and the adversarial hijacked

38:23.960 --> 38:24.680
road signs.

38:25.440 --> 38:30.800
The burning existential question is, how do we fix this?

38:31.200 --> 38:33.220
That's the million dollar question.

38:33.220 --> 38:38.800
How do we engineer fragments that can survive the brutal thermodynamics of the clip economy

38:38.800 --> 38:40.380
without losing their soul?

38:41.140 --> 38:45.500
How do we build road signs that mathematically cannot be tampered with?

38:45.740 --> 38:51.660
This takes us to the constructive half of Fliction's paper, Phase 5, the cure admissible fragments

38:51.660 --> 38:53.220
and reconstruction pressure.

38:53.220 --> 38:54.580
A admissible fragment.

38:54.780 --> 38:55.760
I like the sound of that.

38:56.080 --> 38:59.520
This is where the theory shifts from diagnosis to engineering.

39:00.440 --> 39:02.400
Fliction outlines the antidote.

39:03.140 --> 39:07.920
If you want to create knowledge that survives the internet, you must forge admissible fragments.

39:08.580 --> 39:13.680
And like the general framework, an admissible fragment has three strict engineering requirements.

39:13.780 --> 39:16.260
What's the first requirement for an admissible fragment?

39:16.260 --> 39:20.200
The first is local transmissibility, or A1.

39:21.000 --> 39:22.240
Let's be pragmatic here.

39:23.080 --> 39:25.160
It still has to survive the algorithm.

39:25.400 --> 39:30.900
It leaves enough inherent engagement potential of theta to actually be seen and distributed

39:30.900 --> 39:32.360
by the vector field.

39:32.720 --> 39:32.960
Right.

39:33.120 --> 39:39.160
You can't just record yourself reading a phone book in a monotone voice and expect it to compete

39:39.160 --> 39:40.040
with Mr. Beast.

39:40.180 --> 39:41.640
No, you definitely cannot.

39:41.640 --> 39:43.040
You still have to be engaging.

39:43.200 --> 39:45.020
It has to act as a valid clip.

39:45.140 --> 39:45.600
Exactly.

39:46.080 --> 39:48.960
But the second requirement is where everything changes.

39:49.420 --> 39:51.460
Global recoverability, A2.

39:52.700 --> 39:58.940
The fragment must carry explicit embedded reconstruction data back to its origin.

39:58.940 --> 40:06.220
It must encode a trace of its prior argumentative context, its dependencies.

40:06.980 --> 40:08.520
How does a clip do that, practically?

40:08.780 --> 40:10.420
We'll get to the architecture in a moment.

40:11.020 --> 40:15.980
But conceptually, it means the fragment is self-aware that it is only a part of a whole.

40:16.700 --> 40:21.300
And the third requirement is compositional compatibility, A3.

40:21.640 --> 40:22.640
Which means what?

40:22.640 --> 40:28.400
This guarantees that if a user organically finds two admissible fragments from the same

40:28.400 --> 40:33.260
original source out in the wild of their feed, those two fragments will naturally lock

40:33.260 --> 40:38.360
together to form a larger, coherent section of the argument without generating semantic

40:38.360 --> 40:39.020
torsion.

40:39.140 --> 40:41.540
So the pieces are literally keyed to fit together.

40:41.920 --> 40:42.220
Yes.

40:42.680 --> 40:47.580
Fliction relies heavily on the work of James Munkers, a famous mathematician in the field

40:47.580 --> 40:49.580
of topology, to describe this.

40:49.580 --> 41:05.020
Okay, I think I need another analogy for partial chart, because topology is way over my head.

41:05.160 --> 41:05.740
No problem.

41:06.340 --> 41:10.620
Think of a massive, incredibly detailed atlas of the world.

41:10.900 --> 41:11.900
Okay, got the atlas.

41:11.900 --> 41:18.060
Now imagine ripping one single page out of that atlas, say, a map of just one county in

41:18.060 --> 41:19.720
Ohio.

41:19.720 --> 41:20.960
That page is a partial chart.

41:21.140 --> 41:24.300
It works perfectly well if you were driving around that one county.

41:24.940 --> 41:27.580
But critically, look at the edges of the page.

41:27.660 --> 41:29.180
It has coordinate lines.

41:29.340 --> 41:32.040
It has little arrows that say it continues on page 42.

41:32.440 --> 41:34.880
It has latitude and longitude markers.

41:35.340 --> 41:40.520
It contains the data required to seamlessly stitch it back into the global atlas.

41:40.520 --> 41:46.480
Oh, so an atomic clip is just a torn piece of paper with a drawing of a street on it.

41:46.540 --> 41:48.120
You have no idea where it belongs.

41:48.780 --> 41:51.440
An admissible fragment is a formal partial chart.

41:51.700 --> 41:53.820
It has the coordinates built into its borders.

41:54.340 --> 41:54.900
Exactly.

41:55.300 --> 42:00.680
And the psychological mechanism that makes this work, the way you encode those coordinates

42:00.680 --> 42:06.040
into the mind of the viewer, is something Fliction calls reconstruction pressure.

42:06.440 --> 42:07.440
Reconstruction pressure.

42:07.520 --> 42:08.240
Tell me about that.

42:08.240 --> 42:16.140
This is a radical, almost heretical departure from how content is made and marketed today.

42:16.920 --> 42:22.840
A mainstream clip, as we've discussed, maximizes engagement by resolving tension immediately.

42:23.420 --> 42:24.840
It gives you fast closure.

42:25.340 --> 42:26.540
System one dopamine.

42:26.840 --> 42:27.600
Right, the pinch line.

42:28.040 --> 42:33.140
An admissible fragment, however, stabilizes tension without resolving it completely.

42:33.140 --> 42:38.240
It calibrates a specific, calculated prediction error in the brain.

42:38.360 --> 42:39.360
Wait, wait, stop right there.

42:39.520 --> 42:39.780
Uh-oh.

42:39.860 --> 42:44.840
So you're telling me that to survive the feed, we should purposefully leave our audience slightly

42:44.840 --> 42:45.580
unsatisfied.

42:45.840 --> 42:46.160
Yes.

42:46.560 --> 42:51.660
Doesn't that go against literally every rule of modern content creation, copywriting, and

42:51.660 --> 42:52.020
marketing?

42:52.560 --> 42:54.780
You're supposed to give the audience exactly what they want.

42:54.780 --> 42:59.980
It absolutely violates the current dogma, but it does so beautifully and intentionally.

43:00.340 --> 43:03.740
Now, to be clear, it is not about creating confusion.

43:04.180 --> 43:06.700
If you confuse a viewer, they swipe away instantly.

43:07.260 --> 43:08.520
High entropy, lo-fi.

43:08.600 --> 43:09.320
Right, they just leave.

43:09.580 --> 43:14.320
Instead, it is about creating a profound sense of incompleteness.

43:14.680 --> 43:16.820
What does that feel like to the viewer?

43:16.820 --> 43:23.380
The signature cognitive state induced by an admissible fragment is, this statement I just

43:23.380 --> 43:29.100
heard is incredibly precise, it is valuable, but I can clearly see that it is not self-sufficient.

43:29.740 --> 43:34.860
It creates a psychological motivation, a pressure, to seek the next fragment.

43:35.460 --> 43:41.780
Instead of ending with a sealed conclusion, a neatly tied bow, an admissible fragment ends

43:41.780 --> 43:43.020
with a pointer outward.

43:43.720 --> 43:44.760
A pointer outward.

43:44.940 --> 43:45.920
I love that phrasing.

43:45.920 --> 43:47.040
It directs the energy.

43:47.260 --> 43:52.100
In field theory terms, an admissible fragment acts as a sink in the vector field.

43:52.740 --> 43:57.180
The algorithm is a raging river trying to wash your attention out to sea.

43:57.640 --> 44:00.340
A terminal clip just lets you wash away.

44:00.980 --> 44:04.220
But an admissible fragment is a drain, a sinkhole.

44:04.660 --> 44:10.220
It captures that momentum and draws your attention forcefully down into the deeper source material.

44:10.660 --> 44:13.560
It's like leaving a trail of breadcrumbs in the dark forest.

44:13.560 --> 44:16.540
But the breadcrumbs themselves are highly nutritious.

44:17.440 --> 44:21.920
Fliction mentions a technique called writing with projection stable invariance, right?

44:22.240 --> 44:25.420
Yes, that is the technical mechanism for the breadcrumb.

44:25.820 --> 44:30.460
It's not just a catchy slogan or a cheap cliffhanger like, find out in part two.

44:30.820 --> 44:32.460
No, definitely not.

44:32.460 --> 44:40.280
It's a minimal fixed point of an argument that is so structurally sound, it survives extraction without drifting.

44:41.280 --> 44:44.180
It's an idea that cannot mean two different things.

44:44.720 --> 44:48.020
But practically, how do you actually execute this?

44:48.020 --> 44:59.280
Because you can't just take a dense 500-page textbook on economics, chop it up randomly with a meat cleaver, and hope the resulting chunks magically possess reconstruction pressure.

44:59.380 --> 45:00.760
You certainly cannot.

45:00.900 --> 45:05.560
You need a deliberate structure to manage the transition from the whole to the part.

45:06.800 --> 45:12.760
Which brings us to the architectural blueprint of the paper, phase six, the architecture of coherence.

45:12.760 --> 45:13.400
Correct.

45:14.000 --> 45:16.440
You cannot rely on spontaneous order.

45:16.980 --> 45:23.740
You need a specific engineered architecture, which Fliction formalizes as the three-tier manifold.

45:24.400 --> 45:33.680
To make a fragment truly recomposable, the information system must be designed to exist simultaneously on three distinct interacting levels.

45:33.740 --> 45:34.660
Let's build this manifold.

45:34.820 --> 45:35.680
What are the three tiers?

45:36.100 --> 45:40.320
Tier zero is denoted as M0, the global tier.

45:40.320 --> 45:43.380
This is the fully articulated theoretical system.

45:43.640 --> 45:52.000
This is the 500-page textbook, the comprehensive three-hour documentary, the foundational philosophical treatise.

45:52.240 --> 45:56.160
It contains all the complexity, all the nuance, all the raw data.

45:56.300 --> 45:58.480
Okay, M0 is the bedrock.

45:59.080 --> 46:00.820
It's the ultimate truth of the work.

46:01.200 --> 46:02.840
What is at the other end?

46:03.180 --> 46:06.220
Tier two is M2, the iterable tier.

46:06.220 --> 46:15.940
These are the highly mobile circulating units, the digital flashcards, the 30-second TikTok clips, the single tweet in a thread.

46:16.460 --> 46:20.120
These are the things that actually travel through the RSVP vector field.

46:20.440 --> 46:22.080
They are the vehicles of distribution.

46:22.480 --> 46:26.440
We have the giant textbook and we have the tiny flashcard, but there's a huge gap there.

46:26.660 --> 46:28.180
What is the missing piece?

46:28.180 --> 46:36.040
The missing piece, the layer that the modern clip economy has entirely annihilated, is M1, the structural tier.

46:36.060 --> 46:37.020
The structural tier.

46:37.200 --> 46:41.560
This is the controlled projection layer, the dependency graph, the cheat sheet.

46:42.120 --> 46:51.400
M1 is what preserves the relational skeleton of M0 in a highly compact form and crucially provides the transition maps for the fragments in M2.

46:51.400 --> 46:58.900
Ah, okay, let me try to map this with an analogy because this three-tier system feels like the key to everything.

46:59.120 --> 47:00.100
Let's use geography.

47:00.440 --> 47:00.740
Perfect.

47:01.060 --> 47:01.600
Let's hear it.

47:01.820 --> 47:06.980
So M0, the global tier, is the actual physical city of London.

47:07.640 --> 47:13.680
It has millions of streets, alleys, buildings, incredible, overwhelming complexity.

47:14.160 --> 47:17.500
You cannot hold the entirety of London in your working memory.

47:17.580 --> 47:18.060
Impossible.

47:18.360 --> 47:18.920
No one can.

47:18.920 --> 47:25.300
Now, M1, the structural tier, is the iconic London Underground tube map.

47:25.460 --> 47:26.440
Oh, that's brilliant.

47:26.740 --> 47:29.940
It strips away an enormous amount of geographical detail.

47:30.300 --> 47:41.560
It ignores the buildings, the parks, the exact curves of the river, but it perfectly mathematically preserves the relational logic and the connections between the transit stations.

47:42.140 --> 47:44.180
It is a dependency graph of the city.

47:44.460 --> 47:48.020
A beautiful simplification that preserves topology, yes.

47:48.020 --> 47:55.720
And finally, M2, the iterable tier, is the physical painted sign hanging at a single station that says Piccadilly Circus.

47:55.720 --> 48:00.560
That is an incredibly precise way to visualize the manifold.

48:00.560 --> 48:09.840
So if we apply this to the digital feed, what the clip economy does is it drops you in front of a single station sign, Piccadilly Circus.

48:10.080 --> 48:12.140
That is an M2 atomic clip.

48:12.400 --> 48:14.280
But it has deleted the tube map.

48:14.420 --> 48:16.240
The M1 layer is gone.

48:16.400 --> 48:17.720
Completely erased.

48:17.720 --> 48:29.540
And the system expects you to somehow understand the entire layout of the physical city of London, the complex M0 reality, just by staring at a sign.

48:30.080 --> 48:31.800
You are left totally stranded.

48:32.000 --> 48:32.500
Precisely.

48:32.500 --> 48:56.980
This explains so much about educational content online.

48:56.980 --> 49:06.700
This is why language learning flashcards actually work, but binge-watching TikTok's science facts usually fails to produce any deep retained knowledge.

49:06.800 --> 49:08.280
Explain the difference from your perspective.

49:08.780 --> 49:16.060
Well, if I have a flashcard for studying Arabic morphology, that card is a tiny fragment, an M2 iterable.

49:16.720 --> 49:18.240
It takes five seconds to review.

49:18.240 --> 49:26.340
But it possesses an explicit pointer to a latent structural network, the M1 grammar rules I am also studying.

49:26.860 --> 49:30.080
I know exactly where that card fits on the map of the Arabic language.

49:30.200 --> 49:30.560
Yes.

49:30.880 --> 49:38.700
But when I watch a 30-second video about quantum physics on my feed, I have no M1 map of physics.

49:39.100 --> 49:42.000
It's just a shiny rock I look at and immediately drop.

49:42.180 --> 49:43.960
This is a massive aha moment.

49:43.960 --> 49:48.900
The flashcard has built-in reconstruction pressure pushing you toward the grammar map.

49:49.440 --> 49:51.980
The random science clip is a terminal fragment.

49:52.620 --> 50:03.320
If we want to survive the information age with our cognition intact, we have to demand and we have to rebuild that M1 structural layer for every subject we care about.

50:03.740 --> 50:07.520
But practically speaking, once we have that map, how do we navigate it?

50:07.520 --> 50:18.360
If I'm trying to learn a complex subject, or if I am a creator trying to teach one, how do I move a user through this three-tier manifold without over-soming them?

50:18.580 --> 50:20.040
We need a system of movement.

50:20.260 --> 50:26.500
And Flakiron provides a revolutionary one in Phase 7, topological spaced repetition and competitive field stability.

50:27.000 --> 50:32.900
Most people interested in learning are familiar with the concept of temporal spaced repetition, right?

50:32.900 --> 50:42.260
Hmm. If you've ever used flashcard apps like Anki, SuperMemo, or Duolingo, they operate on an algorithm of temporal decay.

50:42.480 --> 50:46.200
Right. The algorithm models the human forgetting curve.

50:46.360 --> 50:50.420
It says, you got this right today, so I will show it to you again in three days.

50:50.580 --> 50:52.800
If you get it right then, I'll wait ten days.

50:53.400 --> 51:01.080
You review a piece of information simply because a certain amount of time has passed and your brain is statistically likely to forget it.

51:01.080 --> 51:03.540
Exactly. It is entirely driven by the clock.

51:03.820 --> 51:09.000
Flakiron proposes something vastly mathematically superior for deep comprehension.

51:09.560 --> 51:13.580
Boundary scheduling. Driven by topological spaced repetition.

51:14.100 --> 51:18.300
Topological spaced repetition. How does that differ from the clock?

51:18.560 --> 51:28.880
Instead of reviewing information just because time has passed, you review a fragment because its direct neighbor in the M1 dependency graph has just been mastered.

51:28.880 --> 51:32.400
Oh, wow. That is a fundamental paradigm shift.

51:32.400 --> 51:40.880
You review an item not because its memory trace is decaying in isolation, but because your frontier of knowledge has expanded to touch it.

51:41.160 --> 51:46.160
It uses the internal geometry of the theory itself to pull you forward.

51:46.500 --> 51:51.300
You review a concept because it resolves an open boundary in your mind.

51:51.860 --> 51:56.140
So it's not a defensive posture, fighting a losing battle against forgetting.

51:56.140 --> 52:02.880
It's an aggressive posture, actively building structure outward from a solid core.

52:03.360 --> 52:10.460
It ensures that every new fact you learn is immediately hooked into a larger lattice of meaning.

52:10.600 --> 52:17.780
Yes. It guarantees that R2, compositional gain, is occurring with every single interaction.

52:18.220 --> 52:22.680
But let's ask the hard, pragmatic question that Fliction addresses at the end of the paper.

52:22.680 --> 52:24.940
However, let's say you agree with all of this.

52:25.040 --> 52:32.820
Let's say you are a creator, a teacher, a journalist, or just someone trying to share deep, nuanced ideas with the world.

52:33.640 --> 52:34.820
Can you just opt out?

52:35.400 --> 52:36.000
What do you mean?

52:36.100 --> 52:39.860
Can you just say, I refuse to play the dirty game of clips and feeds.

52:40.100 --> 52:44.500
I'm only going to publish my beautiful, coherent, and zero treatises.

52:44.800 --> 52:45.880
That is the instinct.

52:46.220 --> 52:49.060
We all want to just log off and write our books in a cabin.

52:49.120 --> 52:49.380
I guess.

52:49.380 --> 52:50.500
But you cannot.

52:51.180 --> 52:56.140
This brings us to the concept of the alternative attractor and competitive field stability.

52:56.700 --> 53:02.120
If you simply log off, if you ignore the thermodynamics of the clip economy,

53:02.620 --> 53:06.760
any system of thought you build will be violently outcompeted and buried.

53:07.260 --> 53:13.040
To survive, you must match what Fliction calls the injection energy of the dominant clip economy.

53:13.260 --> 53:14.960
You have to fight fire with fire.

53:16.020 --> 53:17.920
But structurally sound fire.

53:17.920 --> 53:18.560
Exactly.

53:19.280 --> 53:24.080
Fliction, Sykes, Guy D. Board's seminal work, The Society of the Spectacle here.

53:24.860 --> 53:26.660
The terrifying reality is this.

53:27.620 --> 53:33.040
If you just put a brilliant, coherent, long-form work out into the digital public square

53:33.040 --> 53:37.220
without explicitly building your own M1-controlled projection layer,

53:37.700 --> 53:40.680
the clipping army will find it and they will chop it up anyway.

53:40.860 --> 53:41.780
They will mine your work.

53:41.780 --> 53:47.000
They will extract the pieces, strip away all your careful context to maximize entropy,

53:47.000 --> 53:53.340
and turn your beautiful, coherent work into a swarm of terminal and adversarial fragments

53:53.340 --> 53:55.380
that serve their engagement needs.

53:55.820 --> 53:56.520
Not your truth.

53:56.520 --> 53:59.280
They will literally chop you up and sell you for parts.

53:59.780 --> 54:03.860
And you will have no control over what your ideas mean in the vector field.

54:04.320 --> 54:04.880
Yes.

54:05.260 --> 54:09.640
So the producer of knowledge must act defensively and offensively.

54:09.640 --> 54:12.940
You must define a strategic functor.

54:13.380 --> 54:19.060
You have to deliberately emit your own admissible fragments into the vector field.

54:19.560 --> 54:25.940
You have to feed the algorithmic beast fragments that have viable engagement potential.

54:26.780 --> 54:31.940
They need hi-fi, but that actively act as those sinks we discussed.

54:32.100 --> 54:33.420
They have to pull people back.

54:33.420 --> 54:38.240
They must forcefully channel people's attention back to your source map.

54:38.800 --> 54:41.800
You have to control the fragmentation process yourself.

54:42.220 --> 54:47.740
So bringing this all together, what does this mean for you, the learner listening right now?

54:47.900 --> 54:53.180
The person who started this deep dive wondering why their brain feels empty after an hour of scrolling.

54:53.600 --> 54:56.680
It means you have to change your relationship to the feed.

54:56.800 --> 54:57.260
Absolutely.

54:57.980 --> 55:01.800
You shouldn't try to fight the basic fact that information is fragmented.

55:01.800 --> 55:05.120
Fragmentation is the physics of our current reality.

55:05.820 --> 55:07.460
You can't turn off gravity.

55:07.620 --> 55:08.300
No, you can't.

55:08.560 --> 55:12.400
Instead, you need to actively build your own M1 layer.

55:12.980 --> 55:14.860
You need to build your own structural maps.

55:15.400 --> 55:19.640
When you consume a clip that interests you, don't just swipe to the next one.

55:20.060 --> 55:23.180
Stop and ask, where does this fit on the map?

55:23.340 --> 55:24.160
What is its neighbor?

55:24.380 --> 55:26.280
What prior knowledge is it relying on?

55:26.580 --> 55:29.720
You need to accumulate consistency, not just volume.

55:29.720 --> 55:34.540
And that ultimately brings us to the grand conclusion of Fliction's paper.

55:35.340 --> 55:41.620
We have to fundamentally redefine what it means to actually consume media in the 21st century.

55:42.620 --> 55:45.820
Long-form media is not the opposite of short-form clips.

55:46.120 --> 55:47.540
That is a false binary.

55:48.480 --> 55:55.860
True, retained long-form knowledge is just a disciplined, topologically sound concatenation of recomposable clips.

55:55.860 --> 56:02.220
The current ecosystem discovered the awesome, terrifying thermodynamic power of the unit, the atomic clip.

56:02.740 --> 56:07.340
But in its greed for engagement, it entirely lost the discipline of the concatenation.

56:07.420 --> 56:07.860
Exactly.

56:08.100 --> 56:09.860
We must reclaim the concatenation.

56:10.140 --> 56:14.760
To summarize this incredible journey, we started by looking under the hood at the physics of the feed.

56:15.420 --> 56:21.620
We explored the driven, dissipative system that actively destroys context to maximize flow,

56:22.020 --> 56:25.040
leaving us surrounded by atomic, terminal clips.

56:25.040 --> 56:26.180
The pile of bricks.

56:26.540 --> 56:27.900
Yes, the pile of bricks.

56:28.500 --> 56:32.820
We explored the devastating psychological toll of this architecture.

56:33.480 --> 56:40.400
The semantic torsion that tears our cognition apart, leaving us burnt out, holding pieces of a puzzle with no picture.

56:40.400 --> 56:51.900
And we mapped the architectural solution, demanding admissible fragments, rebuilding the three-tier manifold of global, structural, and iterable layers,

56:52.340 --> 56:55.860
and navigating that space through topological boundary scheduling.

56:55.860 --> 57:05.560
It is a profound, necessary shift from passively receiving noise to actively, aggressively assembling structure.

57:06.000 --> 57:11.580
As we wrap up this deep dive into Fliction's work, we've talked extensively about the media you consume,

57:11.700 --> 57:15.020
the massive algorithms out there in the world, the creators building the feeds.

57:15.380 --> 57:18.340
But there is an inward application to this theory as well.

57:18.340 --> 57:23.640
Yes, and I want to leave you with one final, deeply provocative extrapolation to ponder.

57:24.140 --> 57:30.860
We spend so much time critiquing the external algorithms, but I want you to think about your own internal digital world.

57:31.180 --> 57:32.700
Think about your personal notes app.

57:32.840 --> 57:36.720
Think about your journals, the hundreds of bookmarks you save in your browser,

57:37.240 --> 57:43.520
the highlighted quotes on your e-reader, or the quick, half-finished emails you write to yourself at 2 a.m.

57:43.520 --> 57:44.740
We all do it.

57:45.020 --> 57:49.860
Are you inadvertently functioning as a clipping army for your own life?

57:49.980 --> 57:50.740
Oh, wow.

57:50.920 --> 57:57.200
Are you constantly producing terminal fragments of your own thoughts, your own brilliant ideas,

57:57.200 --> 58:03.500
that you will never, ever be able to integrate later because you strip the context when you save them?

58:03.620 --> 58:08.180
You highlight a quote in a book, you jot down a two-word thought in your phone,

58:08.180 --> 58:10.280
and it has no transition map.

58:10.620 --> 58:12.040
It has no M1.

58:12.240 --> 58:16.460
It is an atomic fragment in the graveyard of your own mind.

58:16.640 --> 58:18.140
That is a haunting thought.

58:19.040 --> 58:24.780
What if, starting tomorrow morning, you treated every note you took, every single bookmark you saved,

58:24.840 --> 58:29.320
not as a closed, completed thought, but as an admissible fragment?

58:29.320 --> 58:37.680
A puzzle piece with the deliberate, built-in reconstruction pressure pulling you toward your next big idea.

58:38.160 --> 58:43.540
What if you took the time to build an M1 structural map for your own internal knowledge?

58:43.700 --> 58:48.540
If you change the geometry of your fragments, you fundamentally change the structure of your mind.

58:48.680 --> 58:49.300
Exactly.

58:49.640 --> 58:52.760
What would your personal manifold look like a year from now?

58:52.760 --> 59:00.640
And maybe, just maybe, if we start building those maps, we can fix that x-ray machine and see the whole picture again.

59:01.220 --> 59:03.920
Thank you so much for joining us on this deep dive.

59:04.320 --> 59:08.300
Stay curious, demand context, and keep building your own structural maps.

59:08.880 --> 59:09.940
We'll catch you next time.

